            <div type="translation">
            <p>Chio gave this as a gift.</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>One of eight marble Carrara vessels dedicated at the Sanctuary of Diana Nemorensis.
                    Two of the three griffin heads are badly worn down, as is the knob on top of the
                    lid. The shape of the cauldron imitates the Greek bronze wine-mixing bowls of
                    the archaic period. The vessel is solid and so could not have been used as a
                    container. As for the inscription, the precise meaning of 'Chio' is unclear:
                    Guldager Bilde argues that the name Chio is a Latinized form of Χίων, 'from
                    Chios', and therefore he must have been a wealthy freedman. Steinbauer (in Bentz
                    1998/99) is not as certain of the dedicant's social status, but agrees with
                    Guldager Bilde on the derivation of the name. Guldager Bilde also suggests that
                    the vessel was used in a hero-cult context in honor of Hippolytos, given the
                    funerary associations of the griffin decoration. Bentz argues instead that the
                    group was dedicated in honor of a victory at the ludi Apollinares.</p></div>
            

